Implements the shared machinery for passes C/D/E: turning a resolved `TypedEntry` template into keystroke `Event`s and then into a Plover dictionary entry (stroke â†’ `{^}...{^}` value string). The two profiles (`PLAIN` in `plain.rs`, `SMART` in `smart.rs`) are just different `Behaviors` presets fed through the same pipeline in this file; they re-export their own `build_*_dict`/`render_*` here but delegate all the actual tokenize/interpret/serialize logic to this module.

Pipeline: `tokenize` walks a `&[Chunk]` into `Tok::{Ch, Enter, Mark}`, erroring via `RenderError` if it hits any chunk kind that should have been resolved by earlier passes (e.g. an unexpanded macro chunk reaching here is a bug upstream, not here). `drop_trailing_closers` â€” only invoked when `b.auto_close` is set â€” strips the trailing run of auto-paired closers/quotes (`)]}`` "'`) from the end of the token stream, skipping over `Mark` tokens, and stops at the first non-closer/quote token; this is what makes `SMART` rely on the editor's auto-close instead of typing closers explicitly. `coalesce` merges adjacent `Ch` tokens into a single `Event::Text` run, splitting only on `Enter`/`Mark`. `content_and_move` runs the coalesced events through `interpret` (from `crate::editor`) to get a cursor `state`, then appends `movement_events` if the interpreted state has a `%0` landing target â€” this is where cursor-walk-back movement gets computed against the actual resulting buffer, not the template.

`entry_events` is the dispatch point per entry: `@literal`-flagged entries only take the `emit_struct` structural path when `b.auto_close` is true (i.e., only under `SMART` â€” `PLAIN` never treats literal blocks specially); non-terminal entries (type-append intermediates, `entry.terminal == false`) short-circuit to a single `Event::Text` built from `non_terminal_text`, which strips all brackets and only preserves literal text/tabs â€” no newlines, no movement, and this behavior is identical between profiles per the module doc comment; terminal entries go through the full `content_and_move` path.

`wrap(stroke, events) -> (String, String)` is the final step turning events into the `{^}<serialized>{^}` Plover value string via `serialize` from `crate::editor` â€” the `{^}` affix format is Plover-specific wire syntax and must stay in sync with whatever consumes the generated dictionary.

`build_dict` is generic over a per-entry render closure (used by both `build_plain_dict` and `build_smart_dict` in the sibling files) and returns a `BuildResult { dict: OrderedMap, collisions: Vec<String> }`. Collision detection compares only against the immediately-prior value for that key â€” if the same stroke appears three times with values A, B, A, the second occurrence is flagged but the third (matching the first) is not, since it's compared to the current dict entry (B) at insert time, not the full history. `OrderedMap` (from `crate::json_out`) preserves insertion order, not stroke order, which matters when downstream code emits the dictionary as ordered JSON.

Depends on `crate::blocks::emit_struct` for literal-block structural emission and `crate::editor` for the actual keystroke interpreter/serializer/movement logic â€” none of that logic lives in this file, only the glue that decides when to call it.